that quality.

42:39.557 --> 42:41.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I thought he behaved
outstandingly.

42:41.292 --> 42:42.360 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Democrats should pick their
fights.

42:42.393 --> 42:44.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will have plenty of fights
in the Trump
era.

42:44.662 --> 42:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to blow up the filibuster
rules over this
is undignified and an insult to
the Senate.

42:50.835 --> 42:54.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Gentlemen, thank
you both,
David Brooks, Mark Shields.

42:54.605 --> 42:59.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Judy.

42:59.944 --> 43:04.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Thank you.

43:04.315 --> 43:11.456 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: An
Oscar-winning director
returns with a sequel to a film
that became

43:11.489 --> 43:14.559 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a cult classic 20 years ago.

43:14.592 --> 43:16.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown reports.

43:16.260 --> 43:19.230 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR: Hello, Mark.

43:19.263 --> 43:21.265 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ACTOR: Simon.

43:21.299 --> 43:30.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: So, what have you been
for 20 years?

43:30.308 --> 43:34.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's a fraught
question, all
right.

43:34.312 --> 43:39.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The new film, "T2:
Trainspotting," is about
a group of men, once the best of
friends growing

43:39.584 --> 43:44.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up in the projects of Edinburgh,
Scotland,
coming together after 20 years,
with a wee

43:44.822 --> 43:50.628 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bit of baggage.

43:50.661 --> 43:54.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Director Danny Boyle says that
nostalgia,
even to the point of denial, is
a central

43:55.032 --> 43:56.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
theme in the film.

43:56.868 --> 43:59.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE, Director, "T2:
Trainspotting":
One of their problems is that
they imagine,

43:59.103 --> 44:02.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as men often do, that they can
still live
like they were 20 years old.

44:02.240 --> 44:05.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You're saying
that as you smile,
right, that you feel it
yourself.

44:05.309 --> 44:06.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Very much so.

44:06.944 --> 44:09.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, it's like a -- something
I would absolutely
hold up my hand and admit to.

44:09.714 --> 44:13.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was one of the joys of
doing the film
was the learning process of
seeing how poorly

44:13.918 --> 44:19.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
men age and how wise women are,
whereas we
-- it's not even like we think
we're living

44:19.957 --> 44:21.292 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the past.

44:21.325 --> 44:23.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We just are, and we're not
admitting it to
ourselves for so long.

44:23.995 --> 44:25.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's one of those things
that happens
in the film.

44:25.763 --> 44:31.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you have your cake, you have
your fun,
but you also -- you learn from
it as well,

44:31.335 --> 44:33.137 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I think.

44:33.170 --> 44:39.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The new film is a
sequel to
the 1996 original
"Trainspotting," about four

44:39.877 --> 44:43.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
heroin-using, small-crime
committing, wild-living
young men.

44:43.381 --> 44:50.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Based on a 1993 novel by Irvine
Welsh, it
was a low-budget affair, Boyle's
second feature

44:50.221 --> 44:55.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
film, with then little-known
actors, but it
became a smash hit, one of the
most successful

44:55.693 --> 45:01.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
films ever made in Britain, with
a large,
almost cultish following in the
U.S. and worldwide.

45:01.599 --> 45:06.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: We believed in it
very fervently,
very passionately, in the book
and how we

45:06.671 --> 45:08.406 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
wanted to make it as a film.

45:08.439 --> 45:12.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This is Irvine Welsh's
extraordinary voice
that he creates for these
people, and that

45:12.810 --> 45:14.812 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we inherit in the movies.

45:14.845 --> 45:19.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He gives a voice to people who
are marginalized,
and they are from an
extraordinary city, Edinburgh,

45:19.483 --> 45:21.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but they're from the fringes.

45:21.218 --> 45:25.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The first one was
about this
youthful experience of, you know
can almost

45:25.656 --> 45:26.657 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
do anything.

45:26.691 --> 45:29.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they do, like heroin and all
kinds of
antics.

45:29.727 --> 45:31.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But you feel immortal.

45:31.262 --> 45:35.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But now this is inevitably a
kind of meditation
about aging and mortality.

45:35.633 --> 45:39.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: The first film is
really boyhood,
or, you know, when you emerge
from childhood

45:39.937 --> 45:46.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into those late teens, early 20s
and you feel
reckless and careless, and you
can take all

45:46.043 --> 45:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the risks, terrible risks you
take with yourself
and other people.

45:50.014 --> 45:52.016 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And most of us get away with it.

45:52.049 --> 45:54.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they have -- most of them
have got away
with it.

45:54.585 --> 45:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But they move from boyhood to
manhood, really.

45:56.654 --> 46:01.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You get a little sense of the
beginning, a
glimmer of understanding of
where they are

46:01.592 --> 46:05.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the world and what they
should be and what
they need to atone for.

46:05.496 --> 46:12.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For the sequel,
again based
on work by Irvine Welsh, the
four lead actors,

46:12.269 --> 46:16.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including Ewan McGregor and
Jonny Lee Miller,
have returned.

46:16.507 --> 46:21.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All had gone on to successful
careers, as
has Boyle, who won an Oscar for
best director

46:21.612 --> 46:29.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for "Slumdog Millionaire," and
later made
the biopic "Steve Jobs."

46:29.420 --> 46:33.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you're making a remake like
this, there's
an opportunity, because you have
a built-in

46:33.391 --> 46:38.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
audience, in some sense, but
isn't there also
kind of, I don't know, albatross
or something

46:38.996 --> 46:39.997 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of expectations?

46:40.031 --> 46:42.099 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Oh, totally.

46:42.133 --> 46:45.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you have to learn very
quickly to take
off the albatross.

46:45.403 --> 46:49.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Otherwise, it just gets heavier
and heavier,
worrying about what people will
think of us

46:49.206 --> 46:50.307 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
going back.

46:50.341 --> 46:52.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You just say,
don't blow it,
right?

46:52.410 --> 46:54.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have this memory of a film I
love.

46:54.111 --> 46:55.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANNY BOYLE: Yes.

46:55.112 --> 46:57.148 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The affection for the first film
was palpable.

46:57.181 --> 46:59.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, indeed, that was one of the
reasons we
went back to it.

46:59.817 --> 47:01.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There was still an appetite for
these characters.

47:01.886 --> 47:08.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, yes, you're concerned about
not besmirching
the original and the memory of
the original.

47:08.426 --> 47:14.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we felt -- and we tried 10
years ago,
and we abandoned that attempt,
because it

47:14.131 --> 47:18.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would have disappointed people,
we knew, because
it was just a rehash of the
original.

47:18.569 --> 47:19.970 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was kind of like a caper.

47:20.004 --> 47:24.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: "T2" is no
rehash, but it does
pay homage.

47:24.842 --> 47:30.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Scenes are recreated from the
original, again
addressing addiction at times,
but equally

47:30.047 --> 47:31.649 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about the bonds of friendship.

47:31.682 --> 47:36.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: I need to detox the
system.

47:36.353 --> 47:38.355 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR: Detox the system.

47:38.389 --> 47:40.357 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does that even mean?

47:40.391 --> 47:42.259 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't mean anything.

47:42.293 --> 47:44.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not getting out of your
body that's the
problem.

47:44.061 --> 47:45.362 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's getting out of your mind.

47:45.396 --> 47:46.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You are an addict.

47:46.597 --> 47:48.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Obvious question
is, why go
back?

47:48.899 --> 47:50.568 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANNY BOYLE: Yes.

47:50.601 --> 47:55.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, because I think it is kind
of -- it
is a natural inclination in
human beings.

47:55.272 --> 48:00.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The past is alive in us, and you
often ignore
it for long periods of time.

48:00.044 --> 48:01.011 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But there is it.

48:01.045 --> 48:02.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Yes, but there it
is.

48:02.880 --> 48:06.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why we have those
catchup moments
where you go, it's not, is it,
20 years like

48:06.317 --> 48:08.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that?

48:08.085 --> 48:10.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And to the extent
that we're
talking about a film about aging
men, you're

48:10.488 --> 48:11.455 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
older, too.

48:11.489 --> 48:13.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANNY BOYLE: I am.

48:13.190 --> 48:16.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Did you feel any
trepidation
about going back to your early
period?

48:16.827 --> 48:22.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Oh, yes, because
you think -- you're
measuring yourself against the
past, really.

48:22.099 --> 48:23.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Oh, you feel
that?

48:23.100 --> 48:25.002 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Oh, yes, very much
so, yes.

48:25.035 --> 48:30.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I also -- because I have a
philosophy, a belief,
which I can see in many, many
other directors

48:30.040 --> 48:34.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that your early work is your
best work, because
you don't know what you're
doing.

48:34.612 --> 48:37.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I certainly felt that way
when we were
making the first
"Trainspotting."

48:37.681 --> 48:41.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were in the dark, me and the
actors, but
none of us had much experience.

48:41.619 --> 48:45.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you're taking huge risks,
ridiculous
risks, a bit like the bravado of
the characters

48:46.023 --> 48:47.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in a way.

48:47.758 --> 48:50.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, when you come to a
later one and
you look back, then you begin to
simulate

48:50.995 --> 48:55.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some of that innocence and some
of that naivete
work and that freshness really.

48:55.633 --> 48:57.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I hope some of that is in
the new movie
as well.

48:57.902 --> 49:00.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's an
interesting philosophy
of life and directing.

49:00.538 --> 49:02.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's all downhill from here.

49:02.106 --> 49:03.140 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

49:03.174 --> 49:04.141 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

49:04.175 --> 49:05.576 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANNY BOYLE: Absolutely, yes.

49:05.609 --> 49:08.279 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: "T2:
Trainspotting" opens around
the country today.

49:08.312 --> 49:14.952 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jeffrey Brown.

49:14.985 --> 49:28.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Nato Thompson is
a curator
of public art, and the author of
the recent

49:28.465 --> 49:30.434 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
book "Culture as Weapon."

49:30.467 --> 49:36.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, he offers his Humble
Opinion on the
confusion created by charitable
advertising.

49:36.740 --> 49:38.475 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Have a listen.

49:38.509 --> 49:40.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATO THOMPSON, Author, "Culture
as Weapon":
Like many of us, I was brought
being told

49:40.244 --> 49:42.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I should make the world a better
place.

49:42.112 --> 49:46.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a curator of contemporary art
in our public
spaces, I often work with
artists who share

49:46.483 --> 49:47.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this basic common value.

49:47.918 --> 49:52.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to rectify social
injustices and to
help our fellow humans.

49:52.489 --> 49:55.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Call it do-gooder art, for lack
of a better
term.

49:55.693 --> 49:59.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have seen a growing interest
in corporations
wanting to support public art.

50:00.030 --> 50:06.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while I too want to go after
the money,
sometimes, I have to stop and
ask, is corporately

50:06.203 --> 50:08.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
funded art just an
advertisement?

50:08.839 --> 50:10.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Am I being paranoid?

50:10.541 --> 50:13.677 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Am I a pawn in someone else's
game?

50:13.711 --> 50:15.512 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't think it is just me.

50:15.546 --> 50:19.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I suspect we must all admit a
bit of confusion
over what is an advertisement
and what is

50:19.783 --> 50:21.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
actual social good.

50:21.619 --> 50:27.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, every October, a
particular color
arrives that epitomizes this
phenomena: pink.

50:27.558 --> 50:29.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is the color of breast cancer
awareness.

50:29.894 --> 50:32.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, believe me, I can't imagine
a more important
disease to fight.

50:32.863 --> 50:37.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, please, don't take my
criticism of pink
to be a critique of the actual
work fighting

50:37.201 --> 50:39.036 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
breast cancer.

50:39.069 --> 50:43.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I have also seen, as I am
sure you have,
a lot of sponsors jump on the
pink bandwagon.

50:43.941 --> 50:46.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sports teams have literally
turned pink, from
cleat to helmet.

50:46.810 --> 50:48.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Soup cans turn pink.

50:48.445 --> 50:49.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Bowling balls turn pink.

50:49.980 --> 50:52.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Even military fighter jets have
turned pink.

50:52.650 --> 50:58.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I'm all for awareness, but,
certainly,
some businesses see the pink
color as an opportunity

50:58.689 --> 51:01.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to appeal to the female consumer
market.

51:01.225 --> 51:03.961 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now, I'm just guessing here.

51:03.994 --> 51:04.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This approach actually has a
name.

51:04.995 --> 51:07.097 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is called cause-related
marketing.

51:07.131 --> 51:11.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One could easily call it a
win-win, and, sometimes,
my artists and I are the lucky
recipients.

51:11.869 --> 51:17.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Social justice causes get, well,
money, and
sponsors get the benefit of
looking moral.

51:17.207 --> 51:20.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For those of a more cynical
persuasion, they
might see such efforts as a bit
of a shell

51:20.811 --> 51:25.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
game, where a company distracts
with the image
of doing good to take the eyes
off practices

51:25.649 --> 51:27.251 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that are not.

51:27.284 --> 51:31.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You notice this even at the
Academy Awards
of advertising, the Super Bowl.

51:31.255 --> 51:34.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of those ads seem to have
this feeling
as though they are actually out
to do good

51:34.792 --> 51:35.759 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the world.

51:35.793 --> 51:37.161 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Maybe they are.

